+## RESEARCH METHODOLOGY & LIMITATIONS
+
+### Data Sources
+- Public app store reviews (aggregated knowledge)
+- Reddit discussions (/r/productivity, /r/sleep, etc.)
+- Product Hunt discussions
+- Trustpilot and similar review sites
+- User interviews and testimonials (public)
+- App analytics and usage pattern inference
+
+### Limitations
+1. **Sampling Bias:** Negative reviews overrepresented
+2. **Selection Bias:** Vocal users ≠ all users
+3. **Recency Bias:** Recent reviews weighted heavily
+4. **Verifiability:** Can't access current live reviews in this environment
+5. **Cross-Platform Differences:** iOS vs Android may differ significantly
+6. **Regional Variation:** English-language reviews only
+
+### Recommended Next Steps for Your Team
+
+1. **Verify with Live Data**
+   - Scrape current App Store reviews (iOS, Android)
+   - Use review scraping tools (Sensor Tower, App Annie, etc.)
+   - Quantify frequency of complaint/praise themes
+   - Extract direct quotes for research artifact
+
+2. **Conduct User Interviews**
+   - Interview 3-5 users per app
+   - Focus on wake-up accountability behavior
+   - Explore mental models of snooze, habits, streaks
+   - Document exact pain points and desires
+
+3. **Competitive Usage Testing**
+   - Download and use each app for 1-2 weeks
+   - Experience onboarding personally
+   - Test core flows (alarm dismissal, habit tracking)
+   - Note UX pain points directly
+
+4. **Reddit Deep Dive**
+   - Search relevant subreddits with specific queries
+   - Aggregate common complaint threads
+   - Identify emerging user segments
+   - Extract feature requests from discussions
+
+5. **Feature Frequency Analysis**
+   - Quantify how many reviews mention each complaint
+   - Weight by review helpfulness/rating
+   - Create ranked feature request list
+   - Identify high-impact fixes
